  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial of Gratitude for the Imperial Dispatch of Official Armies to Escort Our National Envoy
  author: Anonymous
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your vast magnanimity embraces all things, nurturing life with steadfast benevolence. Your divine wisdom flows boundless, extending tender governance to distant lands. Such grace, engraved upon our very bones, is unforgettable—our entire nation rejoices as one.

    I humbly reflect that in my foolishness, I have been undeservedly blessed to encounter your sagacious rule. Yet I have rendered no service in return, knowing only to observe with utmost reverence the protocols of tributary visitation. When the grievances of the frontier tribes arose and the borderlands trembled with alarm, when our envoys traveled to and fro and we constantly feared the roads might be blocked—how could one such as I imagine that my humble sincerity would find its way to your throne, earning the bestowal of your gracious decree?

    And now, as your humble servant returns home, you have specially commanded official armies to escort him—a kindness so rare it has scarcely been seen in ages past. This flows from your majesty, whose illumination spreads like sun and moon, whose care encompasses heaven and earth. You follow the ancient principles that bid rulers cherish those afar, and you embody the compassion of the sage who extends benevolence to lesser nations. Thus has our humble land been granted the extraordinary honor of your particular regard.

    Your servant shall henceforth become as steadfast as screen and wall, faithfully guarding the lands of Ki-ja, and shall ever pray that you enjoy both longevity and boundless wellness, multiplying the blessed wishes of heaven's covenant.
  footnotes:
    - Ki-ja (箕子) was a legendary sage-king credited with establishing civilization in ancient Korea, making him a symbol of legitimate Korean sovereignty in classical texts.
    - The reference to 'tributary visitation' (朝聘) reflects the formal diplomatic protocol between Korea and China during the classical period.
    - The 'blessed wishes of heaven's covenant' (華封) alludes to ancient Chinese blessings for rulers, adapted here to express loyalty within the hierarchical relationship.
